<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="190" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,152,1223]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,873,899]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Etymology</emphasis>
: Dedicated to Mariom A. Carvajal, in recognition of her work on pentatomoid taxonomy, especially in understudied groups such as the 
<taxonomicName box="[560,768,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Acanthosomatidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1864" box="[828,1006,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Tessaratomidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tessaratomidae</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, the first author, who is her husband, recognizes her support during the realization of his doctoral dissertation. This genus belongs to “New genus 1” in the Faúndez (2017) dissertation. Gender of the genus feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="190" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,152,1223]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1016,1043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Comments:</emphasis>
This new genus is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[768,955,1017,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hillieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[768,864,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Hillieria</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant. The" authorityName="Distant. The" authorityYear="1910" box="[1014,1288,1017,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Pseudaelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1138,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Pseudaelia</emphasis>
Distant. The
</taxonomicName>
shape of the head, with the open, broad and rounded paraclypei (
<figureCitation box="[731,809,1053,1079]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1490]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mariomella singularis gen. et sp. nov. A. Habitus (Scale = 1mm); B. External female genitalia, ventral view (Scale = 1mm); C. Male pygophore, dorsal view (Scale = 0.5 mm); D. Tibia (Scale = 1.5 mm); E. Male paramere lateral view (Scale = 0.1mm); F. Metapleuron (Scale = 0.7mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373069/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
) will help distinguish this genus. The head is triangular, apically acute, with contiguous paraclypei in 
<taxonomicName box="[664,753,1089,1115]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phytolaccaceae" genus="Hilleria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[664,753,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Hilleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and subtriangular and broad in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant. The" authorityYear="1910" box="[1122,1246,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Pseudaelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1122,1246,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Pseudaelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; with paraclypei rounded at level of the anteclypeus, or sometimes contiguous beyond it. The shape of the anterolateral angles of the pronotum, relatively wide and oriented anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[726,807,1161,1187]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1490]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mariomella singularis gen. et sp. nov. A. Habitus (Scale = 1mm); B. External female genitalia, ventral view (Scale = 1mm); C. Male pygophore, dorsal view (Scale = 0.5 mm); D. Tibia (Scale = 1.5 mm); E. Male paramere lateral view (Scale = 0.1mm); F. Metapleuron (Scale = 0.7mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373069/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), and the non-sulcate, tubular tibiae (
<figureCitation box="[1232,1321,1161,1187]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1490]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,417,1445]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mariomella singularis gen. et sp. nov. A. Habitus (Scale = 1mm); B. External female genitalia, ventral view (Scale = 1mm); C. Male pygophore, dorsal view (Scale = 0.5 mm); D. Tibia (Scale = 1.5 mm); E. Male paramere lateral view (Scale = 0.1mm); F. Metapleuron (Scale = 0.7mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373069/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
), separate this genus from both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[389,485,1197,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hillieria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[389,485,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Hillieria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant. The" authorityYear="1910" box="[540,664,1197,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Pseudaelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[540,664,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Pseudaelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, a key to the genera of Aeptini is provided below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
